        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-01-14 19:10:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2\n\nIs this test only so slow in our test environment, or on real disks also?\n\nI don't mind this patch landing, since we are testing this functionality on ldiskfs still (in theory it should be the same). \n\nA better long-term approach (to be done in a separate patch) would be to run some smoke test (or just leverage some other test creating a bunch of files) at the start on sanity to get an estimate of the create rate in the current system and save it into some global file, like /var/tmp/lustre-create-rate, and use the estimate to determine how long this test will run. If it is too long (say 5 min for SLOW=no, maybe 20 minutes for SLOW!=no) then the test is skipped.\n\nThat would allow the test to run in the future if ZFS speeds up, or if it runs on faster hardware.  I think there are a few other tests skipped because ZFS-on-LVM-on-VM-on-single-disk is slow, but that won't always be the case (e.g. developer testing, or if we start to run some tests on real nodes with real disks).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
